english:
  title: Postscript to a Collection of Poems by Sung Chung-am
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven's gifts to all things are rarely complete. Thus it gives horns but weakens the teeth, bestows wings but limits the feet. The swift horse stumbles in its gait, and the scholar skilled in prose falls short in poetry. Should there be one with horns yet strong teeth, with wings yet four sturdy legs, swift in running yet graceful in walking, masterful in poetry yet accomplished in prose—such a being would be rare among all creation. Yet I had never witnessed it until I found it in the son of the Sung family.

    In the autumn of the year Sinhai, I was appointed keeper of the National University. Three days after taking office, according to established protocol, I gathered the learned masters to examine the students. The examination topic was set as formal prose. The work of young Sung Chung-am stood foremost among all submissions—truly skilled in regulated couplets. Later, at monthly examinations in the academy, he produced several fu that soared with the spirit of clouds themselves—a master of the grand style. He also wrote a discourse on Confucius and Yanzi that surpassed others by a full measure—accomplished indeed in composition. I marveled at the wholeness of his talents.

    One day my son brought to me a slim volume of miscellaneous verses, saying, "See what Sung has written." I lit the lamp and read carefully through the night, savoring each line more deeply as I progressed. What abundance! What mastery! Only then did I realize that Sung Chung-am is also gifted in poetry.

    Alas, literary talents have never flourished as they did in Tang and Song. Yet Li Bai and Du Fu earned fame through poetry alone, while Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan were celebrated for prose. Sima Guang confessed he could not master regulated forms, and Zeng Zifgu was said to lack skill in verse. Should true universal talent exist, surely these worthy men would possess it—yet their excellence was limited to single domains. How could we doubt that talent is indeed rare?

    Yet of Sung Chung-am one might say: behold one with both horns and strong teeth, wings and four fleet legs, swift in gallop and graceful in walk—all at once!

    And yet I observe: when scholars pursue the arts, it is as craftsmen plying their trades. Consider a maker of leather shoes who says, "I have no other skill; this alone is my mastery." Test his craft and find it worthy of admiration. But another declares, "I am different. I make boots and shoes and saddles and straps—one man embodying many skills." Yet his wares prove common and coarse. Compared to the specialist's work, he achieves nothing comparable. Why? Because one pursues depth while the other spreads himself thin.

    But young Sung possesses vigorous years and pure spirit, with great aspirations and distant vision. Let him apply himself with full devotion, and even a hundred arts shall reach their perfection under his hand. Press on, Chung-am! Knowing that Heaven has lavished its gifts upon you alone, I speak these words.
  footnotes:
    - Sinhai year refers to 1371 in the Korean calendar system.
    - The formal prose examination (箋文) and regulated couplet style (四六) were standard literary forms in East Asian examinations.
    - Li Bai and Du Fu are the preeminent Tang poets; Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan were celebrated Tang prose writers.
    - The extended metaphor comparing literary specialization to craftsmen's trades reflects Neo-Confucian aesthetic philosophy regarding the balance between depth and breadth of learning.
